 <div class="title" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Study site</div>
 <p xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">We conducted our study in the Admiralty Bay area on King George Island (KGI), South Shetland Islands, maritime Antarctica (62°02′S 58°21′W, 
  <a ref-type="fig" rid="pone.0217708.g001" href="#pone.0217708.g001">Fig 1</a>) from mid-incubation (January) to the end of the chick rearing period (mid-April) of the Wilson’s storm-petrel, during the austral summers of 2017 and 2018. Although a major part of KGI is covered by glaciers [
  <a rid="pone.0217708.ref060" ref-type="bibr" href="#pone.0217708.ref060">60</a>], some coastal areas of the island are glacier free and accommodate numerous pinnipeds and seabirds. The weather conditions on KGI vary greatly between years, but in general are characterised by relatively low air temperatures (
  <a rid="pone.0217708.t001" ref-type="table" href="#pone.0217708.t001">Table 1</a>), high wind speeds (
  <a rid="pone.0217708.t001" ref-type="table" href="#pone.0217708.t001">Table 1</a>), and occasional snowfall during the austral summer [
  <a rid="pone.0217708.ref061" ref-type="bibr" href="#pone.0217708.ref061">61</a>]. We conducted the study in the area recognized as one of the main breeding aggregations of Wilson’s storm-petrels in the Admiralty Bay area [
  <a rid="pone.0217708.ref057" ref-type="bibr" href="#pone.0217708.ref057">57</a>,
  <a rid="pone.0217708.ref062" ref-type="bibr" href="#pone.0217708.ref062">62</a>].
 </p>
